<chapter xml:id="chapter-sets" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Sets</title>

<section xml:id="section-sets-basics">
<title>Basics</title>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>object</title>
	<idx>object (informal definition)</idx>
	<p> any distinct entity </p>
</li></dl></p>

<example><title>Some objects</title><p><ul>
	<li> The number <m> 2 </m>. </li>
	<li> The real number line. </li>
	<li> A chicken. </li>
	<li> A basket of tennis balls. </li>
</ul></p></example>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>set</title>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>informal definition</h></idx>
	<p> a collection of objects </p>
</li></dl></p>

<example><title>Some sets</title><p>
	From our list of example objects above, we would intuitively consider
	<ul>
		<li> the number <m> 2 </m> to not be a set; </li>
		<li> the real number line to be a set as it is a collection of points, each representing a different real number; </li>
		<li> a chicken to not be a set; and </li>
		<li> a basket of tennis balls to be a set as it is a collection of tennis balls (though the basket itself is not part of this set, just the container for the objects making up the set). </li>
	</ul>
	However, the answers above may depend on your point of view.
	For example, a chicken could be considered a collection of cells.
	Even the number <m> 2 </m> is sometimes <em>defined</em> to be a set!
	(See <xref ref="example-recur-induct-construct-nat-nums" />.)
</p></example>

<remark><p>
	Formally, we leave <term>object</term> and <term>set</term> as primitive terms in the axiomatic system of set theory.
	The reason for leaving these terms undefined is because any attempt to define them would lead us down a never-ending rabbit-hole of definitions: what is an <q>entity</q>? what is a <q>collection</q>?
</p></remark>

<p>
We will not discuss any axiomatic basis for set theory, but instead rely on <term>naive set theory</term>.
<dl width="medium"><li>
	<title>naive set theory</title>
	<idx>naive set theory</idx>
	<p>
	whatever axioms for set theory the experts decide upon,
	we are safe
	(usually, see <xref ref="warning-sets-russell-para" />)
	to assume that all the mathematical objects that we would like to be <term>sets</term>,
	will be
	</p>
</li></dl>
</p>

<p>
We need one more primitive term to make set theory workable.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>membership</title>
		<idx>membership (in a set)</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>membership</h></idx>
		<p>
		a property of sets relative to other objects:
		given object <m> x </m> and set <m> S </m>,
		exactly <em>one</em> of the statements <q><m> x </m> is a member of <m> S </m></q> and <q><m> x </m> is not a member of <m> S </m></q> is true
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>element</title>
		<idx>element</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>element</h></idx>
		<p> an object that is a member of a set </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> x \in S </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> x \in S </m></usage>
			<description>object <m> x </m> is an element of set <m> S </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> object <m> x </m> is an element of set <m> S </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-sets-defining">
<title>Defining sets</title>
<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>defining</h></idx>

<introduction><p>
	Remember that mathematical notation is about <em>communicating mathematical information</em>.
	Since a set is defined by its member objects,
	to communicate the details of a set of objects one needs to provide a means to decide whether any given object is or is not an element of the set.
</p></introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Listing elements</title>
<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>defining</h><h>by listing</h></idx>

<p>
One way to communicate the details of a set definition is to <em>explicitly</em> list or describe <em>all</em> elements of the set.
Such a list should be enclosed in
<term>braces</term>
<notation>
  <usage><m> \{a,b,c,\dotsc\} </m></usage>
  <description>a set defined by listing its elements, enclosed in braces</description>
</notation>
to indicate that the objects in the list are being collected into a set.
</p>

<example><title>Listing the elements of a set</title><p>
	If we write <md> A = \{ \text{chicken, tennis ball, the number } 2 \} </md>,
	then we intend for the letter <m> A </m> to become a label representing the set consisting of
	some specific chicken,
	some specific tennis ball,
	and the number <m> 2 </m>.
</p></example>

<p>
Here are some sets containing familiar collections of numbers.
Notice how in the first two examples we <q>list</q> the elements by providing a pattern and then using <ellipsis /> to imply that the pattern continues as expected,
and in the second two examples we merely describe what the elements are in words.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title><m> \N </m></title>
		<idx><h>natural</h><h>numbers, set of</h></idx>
		<idx><h>numbers</h><h>natural</h></idx>
		<notation>
		  <usage><m> \N </m></usage>
		  <description>the set of natural numbers</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the set <m> \{ 0, 1, 2, \dotsc \} </m> of <term>natural numbers</term> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \Z </m></title>
		<idx>integers, set of</idx>
		<idx><h>numbers</h><h>integers</h></idx>
		<notation>
		  <usage><m> \Z </m></usage>
		  <description>the set of integers</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the set <m> \{ \dotsc, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, \dotsc \} </m> of <term>integers</term> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \Q </m></title>
		<idx>rational numbers, set of</idx>
		<idx><h>numbers</h><h>rational</h></idx>
		<notation>
		  <usage><m> \Q </m></usage>
		  <description>the set of rational numbers</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the set of all fractions, call the set of <term>rational numbers</term> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \R </m></title>
		<idx>real numbers, set of</idx>
		<idx><h>numbers</h><h>real</h></idx>
		<notation>
		  <usage><m> \R </m></usage>
		  <description>the set of real numbers</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the set of all decimal numbers, called the set of <term>real numbers</term> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p>
	Keep the following in mind for a set defined by listing elements.
	<ul>

		<li>
			<em>Order does not matter</em>.
			For example, <m> \{a,b\} </m> and <m> \{b,a\} </m> are the same set because they consist of precisely the same member elements.
		</li>

		<li>
			<em>Repetition does not matter</em>.
			For example, <m> \{a,a,b\} </m> and <m> \{a,b\} </m> are the same set because they consist of precisely the same member elements.
		</li>

	</ul>
</p></note>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-sets-defining-candidate-condition">
<title>Candidate-condition notation</title>
<idx>candidate-condition notation</idx>
<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>defining</h><h>candidate-condition notation</h></idx>

<p>
Another way to define a set is <term>candidate-condition notation</term>:
<md> \text{set} = \setdef{\text{candidate domain}}{\text{condition(s) on candidates}} </md>.
This notation provides a means to decide whether an object is a member of the set by first using an already-defined set as a pool of <q>member candidates</q> as well a condition or a list of conditions each candidate must satisfy in order to actually be a member.
</p>

<p>
If we write <m> S </m> for the set being defined,
<m> C </m> for the set of candidates, and <m> T </m> for the test those candidates must satisfy to be included in <m> S </m>
(that is, <m> T </m> is a predicate with domain <m> C </m>),
then the candidate-condition notation takes the form
<md> S = \setdef{x \in C}{T(x)} </md>,
and can be read as
</p>

<blockquote><p>
	<m> S </m> is the set of those elements <m> x </m> in <m> C </m> for which <m> T(x) </m> is true.
</p></blockquote>

<example>
	<title>Using candidate-condition notation to define a set</title>

	<p>
	Consider the set <md> A = \{ 0, 3, 6, 9, 12, \dotsc \} </md>.
	We could define this set in a more precise manner
	(<ie /> without resorting to using dots) as follows.
	<md> A = \setdef{ n \in \N }{ n \text{ divisible by } 3 } </md>
	The <q><m> n\in\N </m></q> part to the left of the divider tells us that the pool of <q>member candidates</q> for <m> A </m> is the set of natural numbers, and the test to the right of the divider tells us how to decide when a given candidate natural number <m> n </m> is actually a member of <m> A </m>.
	In words, you should think of the above definition as saying the following.
	</p>

	<blockquote><p>
		Set <m> A </m> consists of those elements of <m> \N </m> which are divisible by <m> 3 </m>.
	</p></blockquote>

</example>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-sets-defining-form-parameter">
<title>Form-parameter notation</title>
<idx>form-parameter notation</idx>
<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>defining</h><h>form-parameter notation</h></idx>

<p>
Finally, sets can be defined by <term>form-parameter notation</term>:
<md> \text{set} = \setdef{\text{form involving parameter}}{\text{parameter domain}} </md>.
This notation describes the members of a set by providing a <q>form</q> to which the members must conform.
Usually the <q>form</q> is based on parameter variables that can range over a set of possibilities.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Using form-parameter notation to define a set</title>

	<p>
	Again consider the set <md> A = \{ 0, 3, 6, 9, 12, \dotsc \} </md>.
	We could also define this set as
	<md> A = \setdef{3n}{n\in \N} </md>.
	Here, the <term>form</term> of the elements of <m> A </m> is given to the left of the divider as <q><m> 3 </m> times a number</q>, where the number is represented by the <term>parameter</term> <m> n </m>.
	Then the allowed range of the number parameter <m> n </m> is given to the right of the divider.
	In words, you should think of the above definition as saying the following.
	</p>

	<blockquote><p> The elements of set <m> A </m> are precisely those objects that are <m> 3 </m> times a natural number. </p></blockquote>

</example>

<example><title>Defining the set of fractions</title><p>
	We could define the set <m> \Q </m> of <term>rational numbers</term> in this way:
	<md> \Q = \setdef{\frac{m}{n}}{ m,n\in \Z,\, n\ne 0} </md>.
	This says that the set <m> \Q </m> consists of all symbols of the form <q>number over number</q>,
	where the numbers can be any integers, as long as the bottom number is not zero.
	However, we need to be a little bit careful here, since we allow different symbols of this form to represent the same element.
	For example,
	<md><mrow>
		\frac{3}{6} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \text{,} \amp
		\frac{2}{-9} \amp = \frac{-2}{9} \text{,} \amp
		\frac{0}{n} \amp = \frac{0}{1} \quad \text{(any } n\ne 0\text{).}
	</mrow></md>
	We really should make this element form duplication explicit in the definition of the set,
	but to do this would be really cumbersome and would be expressing something that is learned in grade school,
	so it is usually omitted.
</p></example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Empty set</title>

<p>
There is one special set, the elements of which are very easy to list.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>empty set</title>
		<idx><h>empty</h><h>set</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>empty</h></idx>
		<p> the set which has <em>no</em> elements </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \emptyset </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \emptyset </m></usage>
			<description>the empty set</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the empty set </p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

<remark><p>
	The empty set is defined by requiring that the statement <q><m> x </m> is an element of <m> \emptyset </m></q> is <em>always</em> false, for every object <m> x </m>.
</p></remark>

<warning><p>
	Be careful not to inadvertently try to prove some property of members of the empty set!
	You will be proving a <xref ref="definition-pred-logic-vac-true" text="title" /> statement.
	(See <xref ref="section-pred-logic-vacuous" />.)
</p></warning>

</subsection>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-sets-subsets-equality">
<title>Subsets and equality of sets</title>

<p>
Often we want to distinguish a collection of certain <q>special</q> elements within a larger set of elements.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>subset</title>
		<idx>subset</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>sub-</h></idx>
		<p> a set whose elements are all members of another set </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \subseteq B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \subseteq B </m></usage>
			<description>set <m> A </m> is a subset of set <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> set <m> A </m> is a <term>subset of</term> or is <term>contained in</term> set <m> B </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram demonstrating a subset relationship.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-sets-subset" width="27%">
		<description>A Venn diagram demonstrating a subset relationship</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/subset.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<warning><p> We also sometimes use the phrase <q>contained in</q> to mean an object is an element of a set. </p></warning>

<claim xml:id="test-sets-subset">
	<title>Subset</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>subset</h></idx>
	<idx><h>subset</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>sub-</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<statement><p> To demonstrate <m> A\subseteq B </m>, prove <m> (\forall x)(x \in A \lgcimplies x \in B) </m>. </p></statement>
</claim>

<example xml:id="example-sets-number-subsets">
	<title>Basic examples involving familiar sets of numbers</title>
	<p><ul>

		<li>
			Every natural number is an integer, so <m> \N \subseteq \Z </m>.
			To emphasize this, we could write <m> \N = \inlinesetdef{m \in \Z}{m \ge 0} </m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Every integer can be considered to be a rational number,
			since for every <m> m\in\Z </m> we can write <m> m = \frac{a}{b} </m> with <m> a=m </m> and <m> b=1 </m>.
			Thus <m> \Z \subseteq \Q </m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Every rational number can be considered to be a real number if we identify fractions with their decimal expansions via long division.
			Thus <m> \Q \subseteq \R </m>.
		</li>

	</ul></p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Candidate-condition notation always defines subsets</title>

	<p>
	When we define a set by <term><xref ref="subsection-sets-defining-candidate-condition" text="title" /></term>,
	we first specify a pool of candidate elements,
	and then a condition or collection of conditions that those candidates must satisfy in order to actually be included in the set.
	But then every element in the set we are defining must first be from the set of candidate elements,
	so our defined set must be a subset of the candidate set.
	</p>

	<p>
	For example, in <xref ref="example-sets-number-subsets" />,
	we provided a definition for the set <m> \N </m> in candidate-condition form where the pool of candidates is the set <m> \Z </m>.
	This definition makes it explicit that <m> \N \subseteq \Z </m>.
	</p>

</example>

<problem xml:id="wexample-sets-subset"> <!-- worked example -->

	<statement><p>
		Prove that <m> A \subseteq B </m> for
		<md><mrow>
			A \amp = \setdef{3m + 1}{m \in \Z}, \amp
			B \amp = \setdef{x \in \R}{\sin\left(\frac{\pi(x-1)}{3}\right) = 0}.
		</mrow></md>
	</p></statement>

	<solution><p>
		There are an infinite number of elements of <m> A </m>, so we cannot check that all elements of <m> A </m> are also elements of <m> B </m> one-by-one.
		Instead, we let a variable <m> x </m> represent an <em>arbitrary</em> but unspecified element of <m> A </m>.
		Since all elements of <m> A </m> have the form <m> 3m+1 </m> for some <m> m \in \Z </m>,
		we have <m> x = 3m+1 </m> for some <m> m \in \Z </m>.
		Check the condition for being an element of <m> B </m> by calculating
		<md>
			\sin\left(\frac{\pi(x-1)}{3}\right)
			= \sin\left(\frac{\pi\bbrac{(3m+1)-1}}{3}\right)
			= \sin (m\pi)
			= 0.
		</md>
		Therefore, <m> x \in B </m>.
		Since the above calculation works for every <m> m \in \Z </m>,
		all elements of <m> A </m> are elements of <m> B </m>.
	</p></solution>

</problem>

<proposition><title>Basic properties of the subset relationship</title><p><ol>

	<li>
		Every set has an empty set as a subset.
		That is, <m> \emptyset \subseteq S </m> is always true for a set <m> S </m>.
	</li>

	<li>
		Every set is a subset of itself.
		That is, <m> S \subseteq S </m> is always true for a set <m> S </m>.
	</li>

	<li>
		The subset relation is <term>transitive</term>.
		That is, whenever <m> A \subseteq B </m> and <m> B \subseteq C </m> are true,
		then <m> A \subseteq C </m> is true as well.
	</li>

</ol></p></proposition>

<aside><title>A look ahead</title><p>
	We will study abstract notions of <term>relation</term> and the <term>transitive property</term> in
	<xref ref="chapter-relations" />.
</p></aside>

<p><dl width="medium"><li>
	<title>set equality</title>
	<idx><h>equality</h><h>of sets</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>equality</h></idx>
	<p> write <m> A = B </m> if both sets consist of precisely the same elements </p>
</li></dl></p>

<claim xml:id="test-sets-equality">
	<title>For set equality</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>set equality</h></idx>
	<idx><h>equality</h><h>of sets</h><h>test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>equality</h><h>test</h></idx>
	<statement>

		<p> To demonstrate <m> A = B </m>, check that both <m> A \subseteq B </m> and <m> B \subseteq A </m>. </p>

		<p>
		This requires two applications of the <xref ref="test-sets-subset" text="custom">Subset Test</xref>:
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> begin with the assumption <m> x \in A </m> and proceed to the conclusion <m> x \in B </m>; </li>
			<li> begin with the assumption <m> x \in B </m> and proceed to the conclusion <m> x \in A </m>. </li>
		</ol>
		</p>

	</statement>
</claim>

<remark><p>
	One could combine both applications of
	the <xref ref="test-sets-subset" text="custom">Subset Test</xref>
	described in the <xref ref="test-sets-equality" text="custom">Test for Set Equality</xref> above into one biconditional:
	<m> A = B </m> is true if <md>(\forall x)(x \in A \lgcequiv x \in B)</md> is true.
	If the logic of <m> x \in A \lgcimplies x \in B </m> is easily reversed,
	then it makes sense to argue <m> x \in A \lgcequiv x \in B </m> instead of separately arguing
	<m> x \in A \lgcimplies x \in B </m> and <m> x \in B \lgcimplies x \in A </m>.
	However, in most cases separate arguments of these logical implications is preferred.
</p></remark>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->

	<statement><p>
		Let <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> be as in <xref ref="wexample-sets-subset" />.
		Prove that <m> A = B </m>.
	</p></statement>

	<solution>

		<case><title>Show <m> A\subseteq B </m></title><p> See <xref ref="wexample-sets-subset" />. </p> </case>

		<case><title>Show <m> B \subseteq A </m></title><p>
			Let <m> x </m> represent an arbitrary element of <m> B </m>.
			This means that
			<md> \sin\left(\frac{\pi(x-1)}{3}\right) = 0. </md>
			However, we know from trigonometry that <m> \sin \theta = 0 </m> if and only if <m> \theta </m> is an integer multiple of <m> \pi </m>;
			<ie /> <m> \theta = m\pi </m> for some <m> m \in \Z </m>.
			If we set
			<md> \frac{\pi(x-1)}{3} = m\pi </md>
			and solve for <m> x </m>, we get <m> x = 3m+1 \in A </m>.
		</p></case>

	</solution>
</problem>

<p><dl width="medium">

	<li xml:id="definition-sets-proper-subset">
		<title>proper subset</title>
		<idx><h>proper</h><h>subset</h></idx>
		<idx><h>subset</h><h>proper</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>sub-</h><h>proper</h></idx>
		<p> a set contained in <em>but not equal to</em> another set </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \subsetneqq B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \subsetneqq B </m></usage>
			<description>set <m> A </m> is a proper subset of set <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> set <m> A </m> is a proper subset of set <m> B </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p>
	Some people exclude <m> \emptyset </m> from the definition of proper subset.
</p></note>

<claim>
	<title>For a proper subset</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>subset</h><h>proper</h></idx>
	<idx><h>proper</h><h>subset</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>subset</h><h>proper</h><h>Test</h></idx>

	<statement><p>
		To demonstrate <m> A \subsetneqq B </m>,
		first test <m> A \subseteq B </m> as usual (<xref ref="test-sets-subset" />),
		but also demonstrate that there exists some <m> x \in B </m> such that <m> x \notin A </m>.
	</p></statement>

</claim>

<example><title>Proper subsets of number sets</title><p>
	We already know that <m> \N \subseteq \Z \subseteq \Q \subseteq \R </m>, but we have
	<ol>
		<li> <m> \N \subsetneqq \Z </m>, since, for example, <m> -1 \in \Z </m> but <m> -1 \notin \N </m>; </li>
		<li> <m> \Z \subsetneqq \Q </m>, since, for example, <m> \frac{1}{2} \in \Q </m> but <m> \frac{1}{2} \notin \Z </m>; and </li>
		<li> <m> \Q \subsetneqq \R </m>, since, for example, <m> \sqrt{2} \in \R </m> but <m> \sqrt{2} \notin \Q </m>. </li>
	</ol>
</p></example>

<remark><p>
	To show the <m> A \neq B </m> part of <m> A\subsetneqq B </m>, you only need to exhibit <em>one</em> example element of <m> B </m> which is not in <m> A </m>;
	<ie /> you need to find a <term>counterexample</term> for the logical implication <m> x \in B \lgcimplies x \in A </m>.
</p></remark>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-sets-complement-union-intersection">
<title>Complement, union, and intersection</title>

<introduction><p>
	First, it is often convenient to restrict the scope of the discussion.
	<dl width="medium"><li>
		<title>universal set</title>
		<idx><h>universal</h><h>set</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>universal</h></idx>
		<p> a set that contains all objects currently under consideration </p>
	</li></dl>
	We will consider all of the following set operations to be performed within a universal set <m> U </m>.
	In particular, suppose <m> A,B\subseteq U </m>.
</p></introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Universal and relative complement</title>

<p><dl width="wide">

	<li>
		<title>complement</title>
		<idx><h>complement</h><h>set</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>complement</h></idx>
		<p> the set of elements of <m> U </m> thar are <em>not</em> in <m> A </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>relative complement</title>
		<idx>relative complement</idx>
		<idx><h>complement</h><h>set</h><h>relative</h></idx>
		<p>
		if <m> A,B \subseteq U </m>, the <term>complement of <m> A </m> in <m> B </m></term> is the set of elements of <m> B </m> that are not in <m> A </m>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl>

<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title><m> \cmplmnt{A} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \cmplmnt{A} </m></usage>
			<description>the complement of <m> A </m> relative to some universal set</description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the complement of <m> A </m> (in <m> U </m>),
		so that <m> \cmplmnt{A} = \setdef{ x \in U }{ x \notin A } </m>
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> B \relcmplmnt A </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> B \relcmplmnt A </m></usage>
			<description>the complement of <m> A </m> relative to some universal set</description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the complement of <m> A </m> in <m> B </m>,
		so that <m> B \relcmplmnt A = \setdef{ x \in B }{ x \notin A } </m>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>Venn diagrams of universal and relative set complements.</caption>
	<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

		<image xml:id="image-sets-complement">
			<description>A Venn diagram of a (universal) set complement.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/complement.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>

		<image xml:id="image-sets-relative-complement">
			<description>A Venn diagram of a relative set complement.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/relative-complement.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>

	</sidebyside>
</figure>

<note><p>
	Another common notation for relative complement is <m> B - A </m>.
	However, this conflicts with the notation for the algebraic operation of subtraction in certain contexts, so we will prefer the notation <m> B \relcmplmnt A </m>.
</p></note>

<example><title>Some examples of relative complement involving number sets</title><p><ul>

	<li>
		Suppose <m> B = \{ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 \} </m> and <m> A = \{ 1, 3, 5 \} </m>.
		Then <m> B \relcmplmnt A = \{ 2, 4, 6 \} </m>.
	</li>

	<li>
		The complement of the set of rational numbers <m> \Q </m> inside the set of real numbers <m> \R </m> is called the
		<term>set of irrational numbers</term>,
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>of irrational numbers</h></idx>
		<idx><h>irrational number(s)</h><h>set of</h></idx>
		and we write
		<m> \I = \R \relcmplmnt \Q </m>
		for this set.
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \I </m></usage>
			<description> the set of irrational real numbers </description>
		</notation>
		If you are thinking of real numbers in terms of their decimal expanions,
		the irrational numbers are precisely those that have nonterminating, nonrepeating decimal expansions.
	</li>

</ul></p></example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Union, intersection, and disjoint sets</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>union</title>
		<idx><h>union</h><h>of sets</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>union</h></idx>
		<p> the combined collection of all elements in a pair of sets </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \union B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \union B </m></usage>
			<description>the union of sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
			the union of sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>, so that
			<md> A \union B = \setdef{x\in U}{x\in A \text{ or } x\in B \text{ (or both)}} </md>
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>intersection</title>
		<idx><h>intersection</h><h>of sets</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>intersection</h></idx>
		<p> the collection of only those elements common to a pair of sets </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \intersection B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \intersection B </m></usage>
			<description>the intersection of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
			the intersection of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>, so that
			<md> A \intersection B = \setdef{x\in U}{x\in A \text{ and } x\in B} </md>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>Venn diagrams of set union and intersection.</caption>
	<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

		<image xml:id="image-sets-union">
			<description>A Venn diagram of a set union.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/union.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>

		<image xml:id="image-sets-intersection">
			<description>A Venn diagram of a set intersection.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/intersection.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>

	</sidebyside>
</figure>

<note><p>
	A union contains every element from both sets, so it contains both sets as subsets:
	<md> A, B \subseteq A \union B </md>.
	On the other hand, every element in an intersection is in both sets, so the intersection is a subset of both sets:
	<md> A \intersection B \subseteq A, B </md>.
</p></note>

<example><p>
	For subsets <m> A = \{1,2,3,4\} </m> and <m> B = \{3,4,5,6\} </m> of <m> \N </m>,
	we have
	<md><mrow> A \union B \amp = \{1,2,3,4,5,6\}, \amp A \intersection B \amp = \{3,4\}. </mrow></md>
</p></example>

<example xml:id="example-sets-union-intersection-number-sets"><p>
	Consider the following subsets of <m> \N </m>.
	<md><mrow>
		\mathscr{E} \amp = \setdef{n\in\N}{n\text{ even}} \amp
		\mathscr{P} \amp = \setdef{n\in\N}{n\text{ prime, } n\ne 0} \\
		\mathscr{O} \amp = \setdef{n\in\N}{n\text{ odd}} \amp
		\mathscr{T} \amp = \setdef{3n}{n\in\N} = \{ 0,\, 3,\, 6,\, 9,\, \dotsc \}
	</mrow></md>
	Then,
	<md><mrow>
		\mathscr{E} \union\mathscr{O} \amp = \N, \amp
		\mathscr{E} \intersection \mathscr{P} \amp = \{2\}, \amp
		\mathscr{E} \intersection \mathscr{T} \amp = \setdef{6n}{n\in\N}, \\
		\mathscr{E} \intersection \mathscr{O} \amp = \emptyset, \amp
		\mathscr{O} \intersection \mathscr{P} \amp = \mathscr{P} \relcmplmnt \{2\}, \amp
		\mathscr{O} \intersection \mathscr{T} \amp = \setdef{6n+3}{n\in\N}.
	</mrow></md>
</p></example>

<p><dl width="medium">

	<li xml:id="definition-sets-disjoint-sets">
		<title>disjoint sets</title>
		<idx><h>disjoint</h><h>sets</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>disjoint</h></idx>
		<p> sets that have no elements in common, <ie /> sets <m> A,B </m> such that <m> A\intersection B = \emptyset </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-sets-disjoint-union">
		<title>disjoint union</title>
		<idx><h>disjoint</h><h>union</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>disjoint</h><h>union</h></idx>
		<idx><h>union</h><h>of sets</h><h>disjoint</h></idx>
		<p> a union <m> A \union B </m> where <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are disjoint </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \disjunion B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \disjunion B </m></usage>
			<description>the disjoint union of sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the disjoint union of sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of a disjoint set union.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-sets-disj-union" width="45%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of a disjoint set union.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/disj-union.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example><p>
	Sets <m> \mathscr{E},\mathscr{O} </m> from <xref ref="example-sets-union-intersection-number-sets" /> are disjoint,
	and <m> \N = \mathscr{E} \disjunion \mathscr{O} </m>.
</p></example>

<remark><p>
	If <m> A \subseteq U </m>, then we can express <m> U </m> as a disjoint union <m> U = A \disjunion \cmplmnt{A} </m>. Similarly, if <m> U = A \disjunion B </m>, then we must have <m> B = \cmplmnt{A} </m>.
</p></remark>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Rules for set operations</title>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-sets-rules-set-ops">
	<title>Rules for Operations on Sets</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>for Operations on Sets</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set operations</h><h>rules for</h></idx> <!-- TODO should have a <idx>set operations</idx> for the section or chapter or something... -->

	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> A,B,C </m> are subsets of a universal set <m> U </m>.
		Then the following set equalities hold.
		<ol>

			<li>
				<title>Properties of the universal set</title>
				<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>universal</h></idx>
				<idx><h>universal</h><h>set</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> A \union U = U </m></li>
					<li><m> A \intersection U = A </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Properties of the empty set</title>
				<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>empty</h></idx>
				<idx><h>empty</h><h>set</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> A \union \emptyset = A </m></li>
					<li><m> A \intersection \emptyset = \emptyset </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Duality of universal and empty sets</title>
				<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>empty</h></idx>
				<idx><h>empty</h><h>set</h></idx>
				<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>universal</h></idx>
				<idx><h>universal</h><h>set</h></idx>
				<idx><h>duality</h><h>of universal/empty sets</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> \cmplmnt{U} = \emptyset </m></li>
					<li><m> \cmplmnt{\emptyset} = U </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Double complement</title>
				<idx><h>double</h><h>complement</h></idx>
				<idx><h>complement</h><h>double</h></idx>
				<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>complement</h></idx>
				<p><m> \cmplmnt{(\cmplmnt{A})} = A </m></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Idempotence</title>
				<idx><h>idempotence</h><h>of set operations</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> A \union A = A </m></li>
					<li><m> A \intersection A = A </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Commutativity</title>
				<idx><h>commutativity</h><h>of set operations</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> A \union B = B \union A </m></li>
					<li><m> A \intersection B = B \intersection A </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Associativity</title>
				<idx><h>associativity</h><h>of set operations</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li><m> (A \union B) \union C = A \union (B \union C) </m></li>
					<li><m> (A \intersection B) \intersection C = A \intersection (B \intersection C) </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>Distributivity</title>
				<idx><h>distributivity</h><h>of set operations</h></idx>
				<p><ol>
					<li><m> A \intersection (B \union C) = (A \intersection B) \union (A \intersection C) </m></li>
					<li><m> A \union (B \intersection C) = (A \union B) \intersection (A \union C) </m></li>
					<li><m> (A \union B) \intersection C  = (A \intersection C) \union (B \intersection C) </m></li>
					<li><m> (A \intersection B) \union C = (A \union C) \intersection (B \union C) </m></li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<title>DeMorgan's Laws</title>
				<idx><h>DeMorgan's Laws</h><h>for set operations</h></idx>
				<idx><h>Law</h><h>DeMorgan's</h><h>for set operations</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li xml:id="proposition-sets-rules-set-ops-demorgan-cmplmnt-union">
						<m> \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} = \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-sets-rules-set-ops-demorgan-cmplmnt-intersection">
						<m> \cmplmnt{(A \intersection B)} = \cmplmnt{A} \union \cmplmnt{B} </m>
					</li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

		</ol>
	</p></statement>

	<proof xml:id="proof-proposition-sets-rules-set-ops">
		<title>Proof of <xref ref="proposition-sets-rules-set-ops-demorgan-cmplmnt-union">Rule</xref></title>

		<p>
		Recall that to prove this set equality,
		we need to show both
		<md><mrow>
			\cmplmnt{(A \union B)} \amp \subseteq \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} \text{,} \amp
			\cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} \amp \subseteq \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} \text{.}
		</mrow></md>
		</p>

		<case><title>Show <m> \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} \subseteq \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} </m></title><p>
			We need to show
			<md> x \in \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} \lgcimplies x \in \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} </md>.
			If <m> x \in \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} </m> then by definition of complement, <m> x\in U </m> but <m> x \notin A \union B </m>.
			Then <m> x \notin A </m> must be true, since if <m> x </m> were in <m> A </m> then it would also be in <m> A \union B </m>.
			Similarly, <m> x \notin B </m> must also be true.
			So <m> x \in \cmplmnt{A} </m> and <m> x\in\cmplmnt{B} </m>; <ie /> <m> x\in \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} </m>.
		</p></case>

		<case><title>Show <m> \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} \subseteq \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} </m></title><p>
			We need to show
			<md> x \in \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} \lgcimplies x \in \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} </md>.
			If <m> x \in \cmplmnt{A} \intersection \cmplmnt{B} </m> then by definition of intersection, both <m> x \in \cmplmnt{A} </m> and <m> x \in \cmplmnt{B} </m> are true.; <ie /> <m> x \notin A </m> and <m> x \notin B </m>.
			Since <m> A \union B </m> is all elements of <m> U </m> which are in one (or both) of <m> A,B </m>, we must have <m> x \notin A \union B </m>. Thus <m> x \in \cmplmnt{(A \union B)} </m>.
		</p></case>

	</proof>

	<proof>
		<title>Proofs of the other rules</title>
		<p> These are left to you, the reader, in the <xref ref="exercise-sets-op-props" />. </p>
	</proof>

</proposition>

<remark><p>
	Compare the set operation rules of the proposition above with the
	<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" text="title" />.
</p></remark>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-sets-cartesian-product">
<title>Cartesian Product</title>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-sets-cartesian-product-def-exmps">
<title>Definition and examples</title>

<p><dl width="medium">

	<li>
		<title>Cartesian product</title>
		<idx>Cartesian product</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>Cartesian product</h></idx>
		<p>
		the set of all possible ordered pairs of elements from two given sets <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>,
		where the first element in a pair is from <m> A </m> and the second is from <m> B </m>
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \cartprod B </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \cartprod B </m></usage>
			<description>the Cartesian product of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the Cartesian product of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>:
		<md> A \cartprod B = \setdef{(a,b)}{a\in A,\; b\in B} </md>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p>
For <q>small</q> sets,
we can list the elements of the Cartesian product by listing all ways of combining an element from the first with an element from the second.
</p>

<example><title>A Cartesian product of <q>small</q> sets</title><p>
	Suppose <m> A = \{ 1, 2 \} </m> and <m> B = \{ a, b, c \} </m>.
	Then <md> A \cartprod B = \{ (1,a), (1,b), (1,c), (2,a), (2,b), (2,c) \} </md>.
</p></example>

<example><title>A special subset of a certain Cartesian product</title><p>
	Let <m> \N^+ </m> represent the positive natural numbers: <m> \N^+ = \N \relcmplmnt \{0\} </m>.
	Then we can describe the Cartesian product <m> \Z \cartprod \N^+ </m> as
	<md> \Z \cartprod \N^+ = \setdef{(m,n)}{m,n \in \Z, \; n>0} \subseteq \Z \cartprod \Z </md>.
	Consider the subset
	<md> A = \setdef{(m,n) \in \Z \cartprod \N^+}{n \text{ has no divisors in common with } \abs{m}} \subseteq \Z \cartprod \N^+</md>.
	Does <m> A </m> resemble some more familiar set <ellipsis />?
</p></example>

<paragraphs><title>Extend</title>

	<p> Define <m> A \cartprod B \cartprod C = \setdef{(a,b,c)}{a \in A\text{, } b\in B\text{, } c\in C} </m>. </p>

	<example>
		Suppose <m> A = \{ 1, 2 \} </m>, <m> B = \{ a, b, c \} </m>, <m> C = \{ \alpha, \beta \} </m>. Then,
		<md>
			<mrow>
				A \cartprod B \cartprod C = \{ \;\;
					\amp (1,a,\alpha), \, (1,a,\beta), \,
					(1,b,\alpha), \, (1,b,\beta), \,
					(1,c,\alpha), \, (1,c,\beta), \,
			</mrow><mrow>
					\amp (2,a,\alpha), \, (2,a,\beta), \,
					(2,b,\alpha), \, (2,b,\beta), \,
					(2,c,\alpha), \, (2,c,\beta)
				\;\; \}
			</mrow>.
		</md>
	</example>

	<remark><p>
		Technically, there is a difference between the elements of each of the sets
		<md>
			<mrow> (A \cartprod  B) \cartprod C  \amp = \setdef{\bbrac{(a,b),c}}{a \in A\text{, } b\in B\text{, } c\in C} \text{,} </mrow>
			<mrow>  A \cartprod (B  \cartprod C) \amp = \setdef{\bbrac{a,(b,c)}}{a \in A\text{, } b\in B\text{, } c\in C} \text{,} </mrow>
			<mrow>  A \cartprod  B  \cartprod C  \amp = \setdef{(a,b,c)}{a \in A\text{, } b\in B\text{, } c\in C} \text{,} </mrow>
		</md>
		but it is rare that anyone actually observes this technicality.
		Usually, we consider these three sets to be the same set.
	</p></remark>

	<p>
	We use special notation for Cartesian products of a set with itself.
	<dl width="narrow">

		<li><title><m> A^2 </m></title><p>notation to mean <m> A \cartprod A </m></p></li>

		<li><title><m> A^3 </m></title><p>notation to mean <m> A \cartprod A \cartprod A </m></p></li>

		<li>
			<title><m> A^n </m></title>
			<notation>
				<usage><m> A^n </m></usage>
				<description>
					the Cartesian product <m> A \cartprod A \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A </m> involving <m> n </m> copies of <m> A </m>
				</description>
			</notation>
			<p>notation to mean <m> A \cartprod A \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A </m> involving <m> n </m> <q>factors</q> of <m> A </m></p>
		</li>

	</dl>
	And so on.
	</p>

	<example><title>Cartesian products in linear algebra</title><p>
		You have probably already encountered the notation
		<md>
			<mrow>\R^2 \amp = \setdef{(x,y)}{x,y \in \R} \text{,}</mrow>
			<mrow>\R^3 \amp = \setdef{(x,y,z)}{x,y,z \in \R} \text{,}</mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
			<mrow>\R^n \amp = \setdef{(x_1,x_2,\dotsc,x_n)}{x_j \in \R} \text{,}</mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
		</md>
		used to represent <m> 2 </m>-, <m> 3 </m>-, and higher-dimensional (real) vector spaces.
	</p></example>

</paragraphs>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-sets-cartesian-product-visualizing">
<title>Visualizing Cartesian products</title>

<p>
Cartesian products do not really lend themselves to visualization with Venn diagrams.
So how should we visualize them?
</p>

<p>
The example we are probably most familiar with is that of the <term>Cartesian plane</term>,
<m> \R^2 = \R \cartprod \R </m>,
where each element <m> (x,y) </m> is visualized as a point in a two-dimensional diagram,
plotted according to the <m> x </m>- and <m> y </m>-coordinates of the element relative to a central set of <m> xy </m>-axes.
</p>

<figure>
	<caption>Visualizing elements of <m> \R \cartprod \R </m> as points in a plane relative to a set of perpendicular axes.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-sets-cartesian-R-squared" width="33.8%">
		<description>A point in the Cartesian plane as a set of <m> xy </m>-coordinates.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="sets.d/cartesian-R-squared.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
To produce this visualization,
we imagine the elements of the <q>first</q> <m> \R </m> arrayed along the <m> x </m>-axis,
and the elements of the <q>second</q> <m> \R </m> as arrayed along the <m> y </m>-axis,
and then imagine each element of the Cartesian product <m> \R \cartprod \R </m> as a point located at a position that <q>lines up</q> with the corresponding positions on the <m> x </m>- and <m> y </m>-axes of the element's coordinates.
This is possible because the concepts of <q>less than</q> and <q>greater than</q> allow us to think of elements of <m> \R </m> as <q>progressing</q> from left to right along the <m> x </m>-axis and from bottom to top along the <m> y </m>-axis.
</p>

<p>
Even though other types of sets may not have readily available notions of <q>less than</q> and <q>greater than</q>,
we may still visualize a Cartesian product <m> A \cartprod B </m> as <q>points</q> in a <q>plane</q> plotted relative to a central set of <m> AB </m>-axes.
In the particular case that <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are finite,
it doesn't really matter in what <q>order</q> we place the elements of <m> A </m> along the <m> A </m>-axis or the elements of <m> B </m> along the <m> B </m>-axis.
</p>

<aside>
	<title>A look ahead</title>
	<p>We will study abstract notions of <q>less than</q> and <q>greater than</q> in <xref ref="chapter-partial-orders" />.</p>
</aside>

<example xml:id="example-sets-visualize-cartesian-prod">
	<title>Visualizing a Cartesian product between finite sets</title>

	<p>
	Consider the sets <m> A = \{a, \alpha, \phi, z\} </m> and <m> B = \{1,2,3\} </m>.
	Instead of listing the elements of <m> A \cartprod B </m>,
	we will place them in a grid.
	In <xref ref="figure-sets-visualize-cartesian-prod" />,
	you might imagine that the elements of <m> A </m> listed along the bottom row make up a horizontal axis and the elements of <m> B </m> along the leftmost column make up a vertical axis.
	But take care that these <q>axes</q> are not a continuum of values <mdash />
	there are no other <q>values</q> between these <q>coordinate values</q> along the <q>axes</q>.
	For example, there is no <m> 1.5 </m> along the <q>horizontal axis.</q>
	Similarly, there are no other <q>points</q> between the elements of <m> A \cartprod B </m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-sets-visualize-cartesian-prod">
		<caption>Visualizing elements of <m> A \cartprod B </m> as <q>points</q> in a grid relative to a set of perpendicular <q>axes.</q></caption>
		<sidebyside>

			<tabular halign="center">
				<col /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
				<row><cell><m> B </m></cell></row>
				<row>
					<cell right="medium"><m> 3 </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (a,3) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\alpha,3) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\phi,3) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (z,3) </m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell right="medium"><m> 2 </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (a,2) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\alpha,2) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\phi,2) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (z,2) </m></cell>
				</row>
				<row bottom="medium">
					<cell right="medium"><m> 1 </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (a,1) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\alpha,1) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (\phi,1) </m></cell>
					<cell><m> (z,1) </m></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell right="medium" />
					<cell><m> a </m></cell>
					<cell><m> \alpha </m></cell>
					<cell><m> \phi </m></cell>
					<cell><m> z </m></cell>
					<cell><m> A </m></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>

		</sidebyside>
	</figure>
</example>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-sets-words">
<title>Alphabets and words</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>alphabet</title>
		<idx>alphabet</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>alphabet</h></idx>
		<p>any set can be considered an <term>alphabet</term></p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>letters</title>
		<idx>letters</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>letters</h></idx>
		<p>the elements of an alphabet set</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>word</title>
		<idx>word</idx>
		<p>a finite-length, ordered list of letters</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \words{\Sigma} </m></title>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>of words</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \words{\Sigma} </m></usage>
			<description>the set of words using alphabet set <m> \Sigma </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the set of words using <term>alphabet</term> set <m> \Sigma </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<remark><p>
	Even if the alphabet set <m> \Sigma </m> is the usual English-language alphabet,
	we do not restrict ourselves to <em>actual</em> English-language words <mdash />
	nonsense words are allowed.
</p></remark>

<example><title>English is not a full set of words</title><p>
	Words <md> \mathrm{math}, \; \mathrm{qwerty}, \; \mathrm{aabbccddijzuuu} </md>
	are examples of elements in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> for <md> \Sigma = \EngAlphabet </md>.
	So, ignoring punctuation, hyphenation, and capitalization, the English language is a <em>proper</em> subset of <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>.
</p></example>

<example xml:id="example-sets-natural-numbers-as-words">
	<title>If digits are letters then numbers are words</title>
	<p>
	Using alphabet <m> \Sigma = \{ 0,\, 1,\, 2,\, \dotsc,\, 9 \} </m>,
	then <m> \N \subsetneqq \words{\Sigma} </m>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise><p> Why is <m> \N \neq \words{\Sigma} </m> in <xref ref="example-sets-natural-numbers-as-words" />? </p></exercise>

<p>
In computing science, a certain set of words is of particular importance.
<dl width="medium">

	<li>
		<title>binary word</title>
		<idx><h>binary</h><h>word</h></idx>
		<p>a word using alphabet <m> \{0,1\} </m></p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>binary string</title>
		<idx><h>binary</h><h>string</h><see>binary word</see></idx>
		<p>synonym for <term>binary word</term></p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

<warning><p>
	Order matters!
	For example, using the alphabet <md>\Sigma = \EngAlphabet</md>,
	the words <m> \mathrm{ab} </m> and <m> \mathrm{ba} </m> are <em>different</em> words in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>.
</p></warning>

<p><dl width="medium">

	<li>
		<title>length (of a word)</title>
		<idx><h>word</h><h>length</h></idx>
		<idx>length, of a word</idx>
		<p>
			given <m> w \in \words{\Sigma} </m>, the <term>length of <m> w </m></term> is the number of elements from <m> \Sigma </m> used to form <m> w </m>, counting repetition
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \length{w} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \length{w} </m></usage>
			<description>length of the word <m> w \in \words{\Sigma} </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> length of the word <m> w \in \words{\Sigma} </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<example><p>
	Using alphabet <m> \Sigma = \EngAlphabet </m>,
	we have
	<md><mrow> \length{\mathrm{qwerty}} \amp = 6 \text{,} \amp \length{\mathrm{aabab}} \amp = 5 </mrow></md>.
</p></example>

<p>
The concept of <term>length</term> allows us to identify some special subsets and a special element of <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>.
<dl width="medium">

	<li>
		<title><m> \words{\Sigma}_n </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \words{\Sigma}_n </m></usage>
			<description>for <m> n \in \N </m>, the subset of <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> consisting of all words of length <m> n </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> for <m> n \in \N </m>, the subset of <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> consisting of all words of length <m> n </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>empty word</title>
		<idx><h>empty</h><h>word</h></idx>
		<idx><h>word</h><h>empty</h></idx>
		<p> given an alphabet <m> \Sigma </m>, we always consider <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> to contain a unique word of length <m> 0 </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \emptyword </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \emptyword </m></usage>
			<description>the empty word</description>
		</notation>
		<p> the empty word </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-sets-of-sets">
<title>Sets of sets</title>

<note><p>
	Sets can be made up of <em>any</em> kind of objects, even other sets!
	(But now we must be careful of the use of the phrase <q>contained in</q>.)
</p></note>

<example xml:id="example-sets-of-sets"><p>
	Consider
	<md><mrow>
		\mathscr{T} \amp = \setdef{3n}{n\in\N} \text{,} \amp
		X \amp = \setdef{A\subset \N}{A\intersection\mathscr{T} = \emptyset} \text{,} \amp
		Y \amp = X \union \mathscr{T} \text{.}
	</mrow></md>
	Elements of <m> \mathscr{T} </m> are numbers.
	Elements of <m> X </m> are <em>subsets</em> of <m> \N </m> <mdash />
	that is, <m> X </m> is a set of subsets of <m> \N </m>, but <em>is not</em> itself a subset of <m> \N </m>.
	Elements of <m> Y </m> are either from <m> X </m> or from <m> \mathscr{T} </m>, so some elements of <m> Y </m> are numbers, and some elements of <m> Y </m> are sets of numbers.
</p></example>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>power set</title>
		<idx>power set</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>power</h></idx>
		<p> given a set <m> A </m>, the <term>power set of <m> A </m></term> is the set <m> \{ B \subseteq A \} </m> of all subsets of <m> A </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> \powset{A} </m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> \powset{A} </m></usage>
			<description>the power set of the set <m> A </m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the power set of the set <m> A </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<warning xml:id="warning-sets-power-set-elements"><p>
	The <term>elements</term> of a power set are <term>subsets</term> of the set in question.
</p></warning>

<fact>
	<title>A power set is never empty</title>

	<statement><p> For every set <m> A </m>, <m> \powset{A} \ne \emptyset </m>. </p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Both <m> \emptyset </m> and <m> A </m> are <em>subsets</em> of <m> A </m>,
		so both are <em>elements</em> of <m> \powset{A} </m>.
		Even if <m> A = \emptyset </m>, we still have
		<md> \powset{\emptyset} = \{\emptyset\} \ne \emptyset </md>.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

<example><title>Power set of a <q>small</q> set</title><p>
	For <m> A = \{a,b,c\} </m>, we have
	<md>
		\powset{A} = \left\{
			\; \emptyset, \; \{a\}, \; \{b\}, \; \{c\},\;
			\{a,b\},\; \{a,c\},\; \{b,c\},\; \{a,b,c\} \;
		\right\}
	</md>.
	Note the use of curly braces here.
	In particular, note that <m> \emptyset </m> has <em>not</em> been placed in its own set of curly braces because it is already a set itself.
</p></example>

<example><title>A set of sets as a subset of a power set</title><p>
	For <m> X </m> as in <xref ref="example-sets-of-sets" />,
	we have <m> X \subseteq \powset{\N} </m>.
</p></example>

<warning xml:id="warning-sets-russell-para"><p> <!-- \label{WARNING::russell.para} -->
	We are not completely free to define sets any way we want.
</p></warning>

<example>

	<p>
	Let
	<md>
		R =
		\setdef{
			\text{any set } X
		}{
			X \text{ is not an element of itself.}
		}
	</md>.
	First note that there exist sets which satisfy the condition for membership in <m> R </m>;
	for example, the empty set.
	So <m> R </m> should not be not empty.
	If <m> R </m> is a set, then it is a <q>candidate</q> for membership in itself!
	Break into cases.
	</p>

	<case><title>Case <m> R \in R </m></title><p> Then <m> R\notin R </m>, which contradicts the case assumption. </p></case>

	<case><title>Case <m> R \notin R </m></title><p> Then <m> R\in R </m>, which contradicts the case assumption. </p></case>

	<p>
	Since all cases lead to a contradiction, <m> R </m> is <em>cannot be a set</em>!
	This is called <term>Russell's Paradox</term>,<idx>Russell's Paradox</idx>
	and is one of the reasons we rely upon <q>naive set theory</q> in this course.
	</p>

</example>

<remark><p>
	One of the ways to avoid Russell's Paradox is by requiring every object, including sets, to have a <term>type</term>,
	similar to how variables in a computer language can be declared to have a type.
	In such a scheme, a <term>set</term> is never just a set <mdash />
	it is always a <term>set of a certain kind of object</term>.
	Then an operation such as <m> \N \union \powset{\N} </m> would not be allowed,
	as <m> \N </m> is a <term>set of numbers</term> while <m> \powset{\N} </m> is a <term>set of sets of numbers</term>,
	and we have a type mismatch.
	And, more importantly, asking a question like <q>Is <m> R \in R </m>?</q> becomes nonsensical,
	as on the left of the <m> {} \in {} </m> symbol <m> R </m> is required to be some type of object while on the right <m> R </m> is required to be a <em>set</em> of that type of object, and again we have a type mismatch.
</p></remark>

</section>

<xi:include href="./sets.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./sets.d/exercises.ptx" />

</chapter>
